# 8. Context Limits

The context window is **not unlimited**.

It has a maximum capacity.

When the limit is approached,

Claude must decide what information remains important.

It cannot continue storing everything forever.

Imagine reading a thousand-page book while remembering every sentence.

Eventually you would summarize earlier chapters instead of memorizing every word.

Claude behaves similarly.

---

# 9. Context Compaction

One of Claude Code's smartest features is **automatic compaction**.

When the context becomes too large,

Claude automatically creates a summary.

Instead of remembering:

```text
120 Terminal Outputs

80 File Reads

50 Conversations

30 Test Logs
```

Claude creates:

```text
Summary

Authentication implemented.

Tests passed.

Payment API updated.

Dark Mode completed.
```

This frees memory while preserving important information.

---

## Before Compaction

```text
██████████████████████
```

---

## After Compaction

```text
█████████░░░░░░░░░░░░
```

More space becomes available.

---

## Why Compaction Matters

Without compaction,

Claude would eventually stop being able to continue the conversation.

---

# 10. Manual Context Management

Although Claude compacts automatically,

you can also control context yourself.

This is useful when:

* A feature is complete
* The conversation becomes very long
* Claude starts losing focus
* You want a fresh session

Claude provides three commands:

```text
/context

/compact

/clear
```

We'll explore each one next.

---

# 11. Understanding `/context`

The `/context` command shows the current state of Claude's working memory.

Run:

```text
/context
```

Claude displays information such as:

* Total context usage
* Remaining capacity
* Categories consuming memory
* Graphical overview

Example:

```text
Context Usage

Conversation
35%

Files
30%

Tool Results
20%

Commands
10%

Other
5%
```

This helps you understand where memory is being used.

---

## When Should You Use `/context`?

Use it when:

* Claude feels slower than usual.
* You have been working for a long time.
* You are unsure whether to compact or clear the session.
* You want to understand which activities are consuming the most context.

---

# 12. Understanding `/compact`

The `/compact` command manually summarizes the current conversation.

Run:

```text
/compact
```

Claude creates a concise summary of the work completed so far.

---

## Example

Before:

```text
Read 50 Files

↓

Run Tests

↓

Fix Bugs

↓

Many Discussions
```

After:

```text
Summary

Authentication completed.

Tests passing.

Configuration updated.
```

The important decisions remain,

while unnecessary details are removed.

---

## When Should You Compact?

Use `/compact` when:

* You're still working on the same feature.
* The conversation has become very long.
* Claude is approaching the context limit.
* You want to preserve the important decisions while freeing memory.

---

# 13. Understanding `/clear`

The `/clear` command starts a completely fresh conversation.

Run:

```text
/clear
```

Everything stored in the current session is removed.

Unlike `/compact`, **nothing is summarized**.

Claude starts as if you've just opened it.

---

## Example

Suppose you've spent two hours implementing authentication.

Now your next task is:

```text
Build Dark Mode.
```

Authentication context is no longer relevant.

Instead of carrying all that information into the new task,

run:

```text
/clear
```

Now Claude starts with a clean slate.

---

## When Should You Use `/clear`?

Use it when:

* Starting a completely new feature.
* Switching to another project.
* The previous conversation is no longer relevant.
* You want to eliminate old context and reduce bias.

---

# 14. Real-World Examples

## Example 1 – Large Feature Development

You've been working on payment integration for three hours.

Context contains:

