# 1. Introduction

Have you ever noticed that you keep giving Claude the same instructions over and over?

For example:

* "Review my code for security issues."
* "Generate commit messages using Conventional Commits."
* "Review this Pull Request using our team's checklist."
* "Always explain performance issues before suggesting fixes."
* "Follow our Playwright Page Object Model."

If you find yourself repeating these instructions frequently, you're doing unnecessary work.

Claude Code solves this with **Skills**.

A Skill is a reusable set of instructions that Claude can automatically apply whenever it detects that they're relevant.

Instead of reminding Claude every session, you teach it once.

---

# 2. What are Skills?

A **Skill** is a reusable capability that teaches Claude how to perform a specific task.

Unlike `CLAUDE.md`, which is loaded at the start of every session, Skills are loaded **only when Claude decides they are relevant**.

This makes Skills both:

* Powerful
* Context efficient

Think of a Skill as a **specialized instruction manual**.

---

## Simple Analogy

Imagine a software company.

You have specialists:

* Security Engineer
* UI Designer
* Code Reviewer
* Performance Expert
* Documentation Writer

You don't bring every specialist into every meeting.

Instead, you invite them only when their expertise is needed.

Skills work exactly the same way.

---

# 3. Why Skills Exist

Without Skills:

Every Pull Request review begins with:

> Review this code for:

* Security
* Performance
* Readability
* Maintainability
* Naming
* Edge cases

Tomorrow:

You type exactly the same instructions again.

Next week:

Again.

Skills eliminate this repetition.

---

Instead you create:

```text
PR Review Skill
```

Now Claude automatically knows:

* What to review
* What checklist to follow
* How to structure feedback

---

# 4. How Skills Work

Claude explained this process in the course.

Each Skill contains:

```
Skill Folder

│

├── description.md

├── instructions.md

├── scripts/

└── resources/
```

The **description** tells Claude:

> "Use me when..."

Claude compares your prompt with every available Skill.

If a Skill matches,

Claude loads it automatically.

---

## Internal Workflow

```text
Your Prompt

↓

Claude Reads Skill Descriptions

↓

Relevant Skill Found?

↓

Yes

↓

Load Skill

↓

Perform Task
```

Only matching Skills are loaded.

---

# 5. Skills vs CLAUDE.md vs Subagents

Many beginners confuse these three concepts.

Let's compare them.

| Feature       | CLAUDE.md        | Skills              | Subagents             |
| ------------- | ---------------- | ------------------- | --------------------- |
| Purpose       | Project memory   | Reusable expertise  | Separate worker       |
| Loaded        | Every session    | Only when needed    | Only during execution |
| Context Usage | Always           | Only when activated | Separate context      |
| Best For      | Coding standards | Repeated workflows  | Large investigations  |
| Persistent    | Yes              | Yes                 | No                    |

---

## Easy Way to Remember

### CLAUDE.md

> Teach Claude about **your project**.

---

### Skills

> Teach Claude **how to do something**.

---

### Subagents

> Let Claude **delegate work**.

---

# 6. Anatomy of a Skill

Every Skill begins with a description.

Example:

```markdown
Name:
PR Review

Description:

Use this skill whenever the user requests:

- Code Review

- Pull Request Review

- Security Review

- Performance Review
```

Claude reads only the description initially.

If the task matches,

Claude loads the remaining instructions.

---

## Why This Matters

Instead of loading 50 pages of review instructions every session,

Claude loads them only when needed.

This keeps context usage low.

---

# 7. Skill Discovery

Suppose you have five Skills.

```text
Skills

↓

PR Review

↓

Commit Messages

↓

Security Review

↓

Playwright Review

↓

Documentation
```

User prompt:

> Review this PR.

Claude checks:

```
PR Review?

✅ Match

↓

Load Skill
```

---

Prompt:

> Generate commit message.

Claude loads:

```
Commit Message Skill
```

---

Prompt:

> Explain authentication.

No Skill matches.

Nothing loads.

---

## Important

Only the **name** and **description** are loaded initially.

The complete Skill loads only if Claude determines it is relevant.

This makes Skills much more efficient than putting everything inside `CLAUDE.md`.

---

