# 1. Introduction

Until now, we've learned how Claude Code can:

* Read files
* Understand projects
* Use Skills
* Use MCP Servers
* Delegate work to Subagents

However, there's one important limitation:

Claude doesn't **guarantee** that it will remember every instruction you give it.

For example, you might tell Claude:

> Always run Prettier after editing a file.

Most of the time it will.

Sometimes it won't.

Why?

Because Claude is an AI model.

It makes decisions based on probability—not strict rules.

This is where **Hooks** come in.

Hooks make certain actions **deterministic**.

Instead of asking Claude politely,

Hooks enforce behavior.

---

# 2. What are Hooks?

A **Hook** is an automatic command that runs whenever a specific event happens inside Claude Code.

Think of Hooks as event listeners.

Whenever Claude reaches a particular point in its workflow,

Claude automatically executes your Hook.

Unlike prompts,

Hooks never rely on Claude remembering your instructions.

---

## Simple Analogy

Imagine automatic doors.

When someone walks near the entrance:

```text
Person Approaches

↓

Sensor Detects

↓

Door Opens
```

Nobody has to press a button.

The event automatically triggers the action.

Hooks work exactly like that.

---

# 3. Why Hooks Exist

Imagine your team always requires:

* Prettier
* ESLint
* Security Scan

after every file edit.

You could write:

> Always run prettier after editing.

Claude might comply.

But there's no guarantee.

A Hook guarantees:

```text
File Edited

↓

Run Prettier

↓

Run ESLint
```

Every.

Single.

Time.

---

# 4. Hooks vs Prompts vs Skills vs CLAUDE.md

Many developers confuse these features.

| Feature   | Purpose               |
| --------- | --------------------- |
| Prompt    | Temporary instruction |
| CLAUDE.md | Project memory        |
| Skill     | Reusable expertise    |
| Hook      | Automatic execution   |

---

### Example

Prompt:

> Format this file.

---

CLAUDE.md:

> This project uses Prettier.

---

Skill:

> Review formatting.

---

Hook:

```text
Whenever a file changes,

Run Prettier.
```

Notice the difference.

Hooks don't depend on Claude remembering.

---

# 5. How Hooks Work

General workflow:

```text
Claude Event

↓

Hook Triggered

↓

Execute Command

↓

Return Result

↓

Continue Workflow
```

Claude automatically decides nothing.

The Hook executes because the event occurred.

---

## Example

Claude edits:

```text
Login.tsx
```

Hook:

```text
Run

prettier Login.tsx
```

Always.

---

# 6. Hook Lifecycle

Claude described several moments where Hooks can execute.

```text
Prompt Submitted

↓

Before Tool

↓

Tool Executes

↓

After Tool

↓

Notification

↓

Claude Finishes
```

Each of these stages supports Hooks.

---

# 7. Hook Events

The course introduces five Hook events.

| Event            | When it Runs                    |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------- |
| UserPromptSubmit | Before Claude starts            |
| PreToolUse       | Before a tool executes          |
| PostToolUse      | After a tool finishes           |
| Notification     | Before notification shown       |
| Stop             | After Claude completes response |

We'll examine each one.

---

# 8. UserPromptSubmit Hook

This Hook executes **immediately after you submit a prompt**.

Workflow:

```text
You Type Prompt

↓

Press Enter

↓

UserPromptSubmit Hook

↓

Claude Starts Thinking
```

---

## Example

Suppose every prompt should be logged.

Hook:

```text
Prompt Submitted

↓

Append prompt to log.txt
```

Now every prompt is automatically recorded.

---

## Use Cases

* Prompt logging
* Analytics
* Team auditing
* Usage tracking

---

# 9. PreToolUse Hook

One of the most useful Hooks.

Runs **before Claude uses a tool**.

Example:

Claude wants to execute:

```bash
rm -rf
```

Hook:

```text
PreToolUse

↓

Check Command

↓

Dangerous?

↓

Yes

↓

Block
```

Command never executes.

---

## Great Uses

Prevent:

* Deleting production files
* Git force push
* Dangerous shell commands
* Editing restricted folders

---

# 10. PostToolUse Hook

Runs immediately **after** a tool completes.

Example:

Claude edits:

```text
Login.tsx
```

Hook:

```text
Run Prettier

↓

Run ESLint

↓

Continue
```

---

## Most Common Example

The course specifically recommends:

Auto formatting.

Workflow:

```text
Claude edits file

↓

PostToolUse

↓

Run Formatter

↓

Continue
```

---

## Other Examples

* Generate documentation
* Update index
* Refresh cache
* Run lint
* Run unit tests

---

# 11. Notification Hook

Runs whenever Claude generates a notification.

Example:

Large task completes.

Instead of silently finishing:

```text
Claude Finished

↓

Notification Hook

↓

Desktop Notification

↓

Developer Returns
```

Useful for:

Long-running implementations.

---

# 12. Stop Hook

Runs when Claude completely finishes responding.

Workflow:

```text
Claude Finished

↓

Stop Hook

↓

Execute Command
```

---

## Examples

* Play sound
* Send Slack message
* Desktop notification
* Trigger CI
* Update dashboard

---

